    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-10-23T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-10-23T03:00:00-05:00" n="350"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d350">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8294: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-10-23T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 23, 1936—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 24—8 a.m.<note n="42" xml:id="d350fn42">Telegram in
                            two sections.</note>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>514. The following telegram has been received from Shanghai: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“October 23, 11 a.m. I am informed confidentially that the Japanese
                            Counselor of Embassy who serves concurrently as Consul General at
                            Shanghai states that the Sino-Japanese negotiations at Nanking have
                            almost reached a deadlock. He is also quoted to the effect that the
                            Japanese authorities are annoyed that while these negotiations have been
                            proceeding Chiang Kai Shek has been making military dispositions which
                            are not consonant with a desire for a peaceful settlement of the
                            outstanding issues.</p>
                        <p>Abend has informed Consulate General [at] Shanghai that T. V. Soong
                            recently expressed the view that as China and Japan had gone to such
                            lengths in the present negotiations in making demands and counter
                            demands, it would be extremely difficult for either side to retreat from
                            its present position without irreparable loss of prestige and
                            face.[”]</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
